Memory allocation
• So far, we have seen two kinds of memory allocation:
// a global variable
int counter = 0;
int main(int argc, char **argv) 
{
counter++;
return 0;
}
int foo(int a) {
int x = a + 1;
// local var
return x;
}
int main(int argc, char **argv) {
int y = foo(10);
// local var
return 0;
}
counter is statically allocated
-
allocated when program is loaded
-
deallocated when program exits
-
Memory in the data/bss/text segments
a,x,y are automatically/temporarily allocated
-
allocated when function is called
-
deallocated when function returns
-
Memory in the stack segment
CMPSC 311 - Introduction to Systems Programming

