We need more flexibility
• Sometimes we want to allocate memory that:
• is allocated at runtime (not statically)
• but persists across multiple function calls (not automatic/temporary)
• less than the lifetime of the program, longer than the lifetime of a function
• We want to:
• Handle data too big to fit on the stack
• Handle data where its size is not 
known in advance
• Allocate the memory ourselves
• This is called dynamic memory
// (this is pseudo-C-code)
char* read_file(char* filename) {
int
size = get_file_size(filename);
char* buffer = AllocateMemory(size);
read_file_into_buffer(filename, buffer);
return buffer;
}
CMPSC 311 - Introduction to Systems Programming

