C and malloc
• malloc allocates a block of memory of the given size in bytes
• returns a pointer to the first byte of raw memory (returns a void*)
• It’s best practice to cast the return for readability
• Though it is not really necessary
• void pointers are automatically promoted/casted
• malloc returns NULL if the memory could not be allocated (very rare)
• You’ll typically use sizeof() to calculate the size you need
// allocate a 10 element int array
int* arr = (int*)malloc(10 * sizeof(int));
if (arr == NULL) return -1;
arr[0] = 5;
arr[3] = 123;
void* malloc(size_t bytes)
CMPSC 311 - Introduction to Systems Programming
// allocate a single float
float* my_float = (float*)malloc(sizeof(float));
if (my_float == NULL) return -1;
*my_float = 3.14159;

